1401","Kirton, Lincolnshire, England":"Kirton, Lincolnshire, England",",, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Coney","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>cony</i> ‘rabbit’ (a back-formation from <i>conies</i>, from Old French <i>conis</i>, plural of <i>conil</i>), perhaps for someone thought to resemble a rabbit in some way or who wore rabbit skin or who sold rabbits or their skins. One York trader with this name in 1323 was a peleter or furrier."],"variants":[{"name":"Cunning","meanings":["Irish and Scottish (Fife): variant of Scottish or English <b>Conning</b>, from Middle English, Anglo-Norman French <i>coning</i> ‘rabbit’, used for someone thought to resemble a rabbit in some way; perhaps also an occupational name for a furrier. See also   Coney  .","Irish: variant of   Gunning  ."]}]},{"name":"Anthony","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual English form of the old Roman family name <i>Antonius</i>, which is of uncertain (probably Etruscan) origin. The spelling with <i>-th-</i> (not normally reflected in the pronunciation) represents a learned but erroneous attempt to associate it with Greek <i>anthos</i> ‘flower’. In the post-classical period it was a common name, borne by various early saints, most notably a 3rd-century Egyptian hermit monk, who is regarded as the founder of Christian monasticism."],"variants":[{"name":"Antony","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Anthony ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":7,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translatio